      textEn: [
        "That evening, Margie even recorded it in her diary. On May 17, 2155, she wrote: 'Today Tommy found a real book!'",
        "It was a very old book. Margie's grandfather once told her that when he was a little boy, his grandfather had told him there was a time when all stories were printed on paper.\nMargie and Tommy turned its yellowed, crinkled pages. All the words they read stood completely still, unlike the text they usually saw on their screens, which moved in sequence. It was awfully funny to read words that just stood still. Didn't you think so? And when they turned back to a page they'd already read, the same words were still there, unchanged.",
        "'Where did you find it?' Margie asked.\n'In our house.' Tommy pointed vaguely, not looking up because he was absorbed in reading. 'In the attic.'\n'What's it about?'\n'School.'",
        "Margie's face showed a look of scorn and contempt: 'School? What's there to write about school? I hate school.' Margie had always hated school, but now she detested it more than ever. The mechanical teacher kept giving her geography test after geography test, and she did worse each time. Finally her mother shook her head sadly and sent for the County Inspector.",
        "The Inspector adjusted the mechanical teacher, patted Margie on the head, and told her mother with a smile: 'It's not the girl's fault, Mrs. Jones. I think the geography sector was geared a little too quick. These things happen sometimes. I've slowed it down to an average ten-year level. Actually, her overall progress is quite satisfactory.' He patted Margie's head again.\nMargie was bitterly disappointed. She had been hoping they would take the teacher away altogether, as they had once taken Tommy's teacher away for nearly a month because the history sector had blanked out completely.",
        "So she said to Tommy: 'Why would anyone write about school?'\nTommy looked at her with very superior eyes: 'Because it's not our kind of school, stupid. That was the old kind of school they had hundreds of years ago.' He added loftily, pronouncing the word carefully: 'Centuries ago.'",
        "'Well, I don't know what kind of school they had all that way back,' Margie said. She read the book over his shoulder for a while, then said, 'Anyway, they must have had a teacher, right?'\n'Sure they had a teacher, but it wasn't a regular teacher. It was a man.'\n'A man? How could a man be a teacher?'\n'Well, he just told the boys and girls things and gave them homework and asked them questions.'\n'A man isn't smart enough.'\n'Sure he is. My father knows as much as my teacher.'",
        "Margie didn't want to argue about that, so she said: 'I wouldn't want a strange man in my house to teach me.'\nTommy screamed with laughter. 'You don't know much, Margie. The teachers didn't live in the house. They had a special building and all the kids went there.'\n'And all the kids learned the same thing?'\n'Sure, if they were the same age.'",
        "They hadn't even finished half the book when Margie's mother called: 'Margie! School time!'\nMargie sighed and went to the schoolroom. She was thinking about the old schools they had when her grandfather's grandfather was a little boy. All the kids from the whole neighborhood came, laughing and shouting in the schoolyard, sitting together in the schoolroom, going home together at the end of the day. They learned the same things, so they could help one another with homework and talk about it.",
        "And the teachers were people...",
        "Margie thought about how the kids must have loved it in the old days. She thought about the fun they had."
      ],
